# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: axial-compressor
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] The **accessory drive** is a gearbox that forms part of a gas turbine engine.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] Although not part of the engine's core, it drives the accessories – such as generators, pumps for fuel and lubrication oil, air compressors, hydraulic pumps and engine starters – that are otherwise essential for the operation of the engine or the aircraft on which it is mounted.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] Accessory drives on large engines handle between 400–500 hp.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] Power for the accessory drive is taken from the central shaft linking the turbine and compressor sections of the engine.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] This requires an internal gearbox that couples the drive to a radial driveshaft or *towershaft* that drives an external gearbox.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] The design of the internal gearbox is complicated by the heat and small space available in which to connect the driveshaft.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] It is usually placed between the compressor outlet and the combustor.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] In turboprops or designs with centrifugal compressors, it may be placed ahead of the compressor.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] For two-shaft designs, an accessory drive will be taken from the high-pressure shaft, i.e. the outer and shorter of the two concentric shafts.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] This shaft comes up to speed more quickly when the engine is started.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] The drive and accessory gearboxes may also be split in two, one driven from each engine shaft, so as to distribute their loads.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] The engine-critical systems, including the starter drive, are arranged on the high-pressure shaft, with aircraft systems on the low-pressure shaft.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] The high-pressure shaft also rotates faster than the low-pressure shaft, which may influence the distribution of accessories.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] To make the best use of the limited space for the driveshaft and internal gearbox, the driveshaft runs at high speed, thus allowing it to be of small diameter.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] This reduces the disruption to the airflow and the size of the hollow fairing that encloses it.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] If it is not possible to arrange a single straight path for the driveshaft, it may be arranged in two sections and linked by an intermediate gearbox.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] This is most commonly required for high-bypass turbofans with large diameter fans.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] The packaging of an engine within its nacelle is a complicated task.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] The accessory drive is usually arranged as a curved casing, so that the various accessories are mounted close to the engine.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] The casing is a pair of light alloy castings.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] Separate machined mounting pads are provided for each accessory.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] The drive within the casing is provided by a train of spur gears.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] Accessories are arranged on both sides of the driveshaft entry, in reducing order of their speed.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] The gears are usually plain spur gears, running in roller bearings.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] Idler gears are commonly used between them, to increase the spacing between accessories.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] Helical gears are sometimes used for the high-torque drives, typically the starter, as these give smoother running.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] However helical gears also generate an end-thrust, which then requires a more complicated thrust bearing to support them.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] The complexity of an accessory drive and its gears is so great that they were used as a theme by the anthropomorphic illustrator Boris Artzybasheff in advertising for the Avco Lycoming company, who were making drive gearboxes for the Westinghouse J40 engine.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] In some engines, bleed air is also tapped to provide power for accessories, as well as a mechanical shaft drive.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] Bleed air is particularly useful when a source of compressed air is specifically needed, either to pressurise cabin air, or as a supply of cooling air to other components (to avoid excess heat, this is taken for a low-pressure tapping, or from the LP compressor of a two-shaft engine).
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] One important use for bleed air is for cross-starting of other engines in a multi-engine aircraft.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] Additional facilities are provided for a centrifugal oil breather, to separate the drive lubricating oil from the overboard breather air vent.
[src:axial-compressor/accessory-drive] Also access for hand-turning the engine, during ground maintenance.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] In fluid dynamics, a **stall** is a reduction in the lift coefficient generated by a foil as angle of attack exceeds its critical value.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The critical angle of attack is typically about 15°, but it may vary significantly depending on the fluid, foil – including its shape, size, and finish – and Reynolds number.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Stalls in fixed-wing aircraft are often experienced as a sudden reduction in lift as the airflow separates from the upper surface, which may be due to an increase in the wing's angle of attack past the critical angle or a decrease in the critical angle of attack.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The former may be due to slowing down (below stall speed), the latter by accretion of ice on the wings.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] A stall does not mean that the engine(s) have stopped working, or that the aircraft has stopped moving—the effect is the same even in an unpowered glider aircraft.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Because stalls are most commonly discussed in connection with aviation, this article discusses stalls as they relate mainly to aircraft, in particular fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The principles of stall discussed here translate to foils in other fluids as well.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] A stall is a condition in aerodynamics and aviation such that if the angle of attack on an aircraft increases beyond a certain point, then lift begins to decrease.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The angle at which this occurs is called the *critical angle of attack*.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] If the angle of attack increases beyond the critical value, the lift decreases and the aircraft descends, further increasing the angle of attack and causing further loss of lift.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The critical angle of attack is dependent upon the airfoil section or profile of the wing, its planform, its aspect ratio, and other factors, but is typically in the range of 8 to 20 degrees relative to the incoming wind (relative wind) for most subsonic airfoils.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The critical angle of attack is the angle of attack on the lift coefficient versus angle-of-attack (Cl~alpha) curve at which the maximum lift coefficient occurs.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Stalling is caused by flow separation which, in turn, is caused by the air flowing against a rising pressure.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Whitford describes three types of stall: trailing-edge, leading-edge and thin-aerofoil, each with distinctive Cl~alpha features.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] For the trailing-edge stall, separation begins at small angles of attack near the trailing edge of the wing while the rest of the flow over the wing remains attached.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] As angle of attack increases, the separated regions on the top of the wing increase in size as the flow separation moves forward, and this hinders the ability of the wing to create lift.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] This is shown by the reduction in lift-slope on a Cl~alpha curve as the lift nears its maximum value.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The separated flow usually causes buffeting.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Beyond the critical angle of attack, separated flow is so dominant that additional increases in angle of attack cause the lift to fall from its peak value.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Piston-engined and early jet transports had very good stall behaviour with pre-stall buffet warning and, if ignored, a straight nose-drop for a natural recovery.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Wing developments that came with the introduction of turbo-prop engines introduced unacceptable stall behaviour.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Leading-edge developments on high-lift wings, and the introduction of rear-mounted engines and high-set tailplanes on the next generation of jet transports, also introduced unacceptable stall behaviour.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] When the mean angle of attack of the wings is beyond the stall, a spin, which is an autorotation of a stalled wing, may develop.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] A spin follows departures in roll, yaw and pitch from balanced flight.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] For example, a roll is naturally damped with an unstalled wing, but with wings stalled, the damping moment is replaced with a propelling moment.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The graph shows that the greatest amount of lift is produced as the critical angle of attack is reached (which in early-20th century aviation was called the "burble point").
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] This angle is 17.5 degrees in this case, but it varies from airfoil to airfoil.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] In particular, for aerodynamically thick airfoils (thickness to chord ratios of around 10%), the critical angle is higher than with a thin airfoil of the same camber.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Symmetric airfoils have lower critical angles (but also work efficiently in inverted flight).
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The graph shows that, as the angle of attack exceeds the critical angle, the lift produced by the airfoil decreases.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The information in a graph of this kind is gathered using a model of the airfoil in a wind tunnel.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Because aircraft models are normally used, rather than full-size machines, special care is needed to make sure that data is taken in the same Reynolds number regime (or scale speed) as in free flight.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The separation of flow from the upper wing surface at high angles of attack is quite different at low Reynolds number from that at the high Reynolds numbers of real aircraft.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] In particular at high Reynolds numbers the flow tends to stay attached to the airfoil for longer because the inertial forces are dominant with respect to the viscous forces which are responsible for the flow separation ultimately leading to the aerodynamic stall.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] For this reason wind tunnel results carried out at lower speeds and on smaller scale models of the real life counterparts often tend to overestimate the aerodynamic stall angle of attack.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] High-pressure wind tunnels are one solution to this problem.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] In general, steady operation of an aircraft at an angle of attack above the critical angle is not possible because, after exceeding the critical angle, the loss of lift from the wing causes the nose of the aircraft to fall, reducing the angle of attack again.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] This nose drop, independent of control inputs, indicates the pilot has actually stalled the aircraft.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] This graph shows the stall angle, yet in practice most pilot operating handbooks (POH) or generic flight manuals describe stalling in terms of airspeed.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] This is because all aircraft are equipped with an airspeed indicator, but fewer aircraft have an angle of attack indicator.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] An aircraft's stalling speed is published by the manufacturer (and is required for certification by flight testing) for a range of weights and flap positions, but the stalling angle of attack is not published.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] As speed reduces, angle of attack has to increase to keep lift constant until the critical angle is reached.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The airspeed at which this angle is reached is the (1g, unaccelerated) stalling speed of the aircraft in that particular configuration.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Deploying flaps/slats decreases the stall speed to allow the aircraft to take off and land at a lower speed.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] A fixed-wing aircraft can be made to stall in any pitch attitude or bank angle or at any airspeed but deliberate stalling is commonly practiced by reducing the speed to the unaccelerated stall speed, at a safe altitude.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Unaccelerated (1g) stall speed varies on different fixed-wing aircraft and is represented by colour codes on the airspeed indicator.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] As the plane flies at this speed, the angle of attack must be increased to prevent any loss of altitude or gain in airspeed (which corresponds to the stall angle described above).
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The pilot will notice the flight controls have become less responsive and may also notice some buffeting, a result of the turbulent air separated from the wing hitting the tail of the aircraft.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] In most light aircraft, as the stall is reached, the aircraft will start to descend (because the wing is no longer producing enough lift to support the aircraft's weight) and the nose will pitch down.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Recovery from the stall involves lowering the aircraft nose, to decrease the angle of attack and increase the air speed, until smooth air-flow over the wing is restored.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Normal flight can be resumed once recovery is complete.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The maneuver is normally quite safe, and, if correctly handled, leads to only a small loss in altitude (20–30 m/66–98 ft).
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] It is taught and practised in order for pilots to recognize, avoid, and recover from stalling the aircraft.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] A pilot is required to demonstrate competency in controlling an aircraft during and after a stall for certification in the United States, and it is a routine maneuver for pilots when getting to know the handling of an unfamiliar aircraft type.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The only dangerous aspect of a stall is a lack of altitude for recovery.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] A special form of asymmetric stall in which the aircraft also rotates about its yaw axis is called a spin.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] A spin can occur if an aircraft is stalled and there is an asymmetric yawing moment applied to it.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] This yawing moment can be aerodynamic (sideslip angle, rudder, adverse yaw from the ailerons), thrust related (p-factor, one engine inoperative on a multi-engine non-centreline thrust aircraft), or from less likely sources such as severe turbulence.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The net effect is that one wing is stalled before the other and the aircraft descends rapidly while rotating, and some aircraft cannot recover from this condition without correct pilot control inputs (which must stop yaw) and loading.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] A new solution to the problem of difficult (or impossible) stall-spin recovery is provided by the ballistic parachute recovery system.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The most common stall-spin scenarios occur on takeoff (departure stall) and during landing (base to final turn) because of insufficient airspeed during these maneuvers.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Stalls also occur during a go-around manoeuvre if the pilot does not properly respond to the out-of-trim situation resulting from the transition from low power setting to high power setting at low speed.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Stall speed is increased when the wing surfaces are contaminated with ice or frost creating a rougher surface, and heavier airframe due to ice accumulation.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Stalls occur not only at slow airspeed, but at any speed when the wings exceed their critical angle of attack.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Attempting to increase the angle of attack at 1g by moving the control column back normally causes the aircraft to climb.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] However, aircraft often experience higher g-forces, such as when turning steeply or pulling out of a dive.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] In these cases, the wings are already operating at a higher angle of attack to create the necessary force (derived from lift) to accelerate in the desired direction.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Increasing the g-loading still further, by pulling back on the controls, can cause the stalling angle to be exceeded, even though the aircraft is flying at a high speed.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] These "high-speed stalls" produce the same buffeting characteristics as 1g stalls and can also initiate a spin if there is also any yawing.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Different aircraft types have different stalling characteristics but they only have to be good enough to satisfy their particular airworthiness authority.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] For example, the Short Belfast heavy freighter had a marginal nose drop which was acceptable to the Royal Air Force.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] When the aircraft were sold to a civil operator they had to be fitted with a stick pusher to meet the civil requirements.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Some aircraft may naturally have very good behaviour well beyond what is required.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] For example, first generation jet transports have been described as having an immaculate nose drop at the stall.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Loss of lift on one wing is acceptable as long as the roll, including during stall recovery, doesn't exceed about 20 degrees, or in turning flight the roll shall not exceed 90 degrees bank.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] If pre-stall warning followed by nose drop and limited wing drop are naturally not present or are deemed to be unacceptably marginal by an Airworthiness authority the stalling behaviour has to be made good enough with airframe modifications or devices such as a stick shaker and pusher.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] These are described in "Warning and safety devices".
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Stalls depend only on angle of attack, not airspeed.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] However, the slower an aircraft flies, the greater the angle of attack it needs to produce lift equal to the aircraft's weight.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] As the speed decreases further, at some point this angle will be equal to the critical (stall) angle of attack.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] An aircraft flying at its stall speed cannot climb, and an aircraft flying below its stall speed cannot stop descending.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Any attempt to do so by increasing angle of attack, without first increasing airspeed, will result in a stall.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The actual stall speed will vary depending on the airplane's weight, altitude, configuration, and vertical and lateral acceleration.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Propeller slipstream reduces the stall speed by energizing the flow over the wings.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] An airspeed indicator, for the purpose of flight-testing, may have the following markings: the lowest-speed of the white arc indicates VS0 at maximum weight with the flaps down, while the lowest-speed of the green arc indicates VS1 at maximum weight.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] While an aircraft's VS speed is computed by design, its VS0 and VS1 speeds must be demonstrated empirically by flight testing.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The normal stall speed, specified by the VS values above, always refers to straight and level flight, where the load factor is equal to 1g.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] However, if the aircraft is turning or pulling up from a dive, additional lift is required to provide the vertical or lateral acceleration, and so the stall speed is higher.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] An accelerated stall is a stall that occurs under such conditions.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] To achieve the extra lift, the lift coefficient, and so the angle of attack, will have to be higher than it would be in straight and level flight at the same speed.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The table that follows gives some examples of the relation between the angle of bank and the square root of the load factor.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] It derives from the trigonometric relation (secant) between L and W .
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] For example, in a turn with bank angle of 45°, Vst is 19% higher than Vs.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] According to Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) terminology, the above example illustrates a so-called **turning flight stall**, while the term *accelerated* is used to indicate an *accelerated turning stall* only, that is, a turning flight stall where the airspeed decreases at a given rate.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The tendency of powerful propeller aircraft to roll in reaction to engine torque creates a risk of accelerated stalls.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] When an aircraft such as a Mitsubishi MU-2 is flying close to its stall speed, the sudden application of full power may cause it to roll, creating the same aerodynamic conditions that induce an accelerated stall in turning flight even if the pilot did not deliberately initiate a turn.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Pilots of such aircraft are trained to avoid sudden and drastic increases in power at low altitude and low airspeed as it may be difficult to recover from an accelerated stall under these conditions.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] During a canyon escape turn, the load factor and stall speed both increase.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] An accelerated stall may happen if a pilot does not keep proper track of their airspeed.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The crash of a Cessna 152 near Harrison Lake, British Columbia occurred due to a stall while trying to escape a box canyon.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] A notable example of an air accident involving a low-altitude turning flight stall is the 1994 Fairchild Air Force Base B-52 crash.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Dynamic stall is a non-linear unsteady aerodynamic effect that occurs when airfoils rapidly change the angle of attack.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The rapid change can cause a strong vortex to be shed from the leading edge of the aerofoil, and travel backwards above the wing.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The vortex, containing high-velocity airflows, briefly increases the lift produced by the wing.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] As soon as it passes behind the trailing edge, however, the lift reduces dramatically, and the wing is in normal stall.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Dynamic stall is an effect most associated with helicopters and flapping wings, though also occurs in wind turbines, and due to gusting airflow.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] During forward flight, some regions of a helicopter blade may incur flow that reverses (compared to the direction of blade movement), and thus includes rapidly changing angles of attack.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Oscillating (flapping) wings, such as those of insects like the bumblebee, may rely almost entirely on dynamic stall for lift production, provided the oscillations are fast compared to the speed of flight, and the angle of the wing changes rapidly compared to airflow direction.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Stall delay can occur on airfoils subject to a high angle of attack and a three-dimensional flow.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] When the angle of attack on an airfoil is increasing rapidly, the flow will remain substantially attached to the airfoil to a significantly higher angle of attack than can be achieved in steady-state conditions.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] As a result, the stall is delayed momentarily and a lift coefficient significantly higher than the steady-state maximum is achieved.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The effect was first noticed on propellers.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] A *deep stall* (or *super-stall*) is a dangerous type of stall that affects certain aircraft designs, notably jet aircraft with a T-tail configuration and rear-mounted engines.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] In these designs, the turbulent wake of a stalled main wing, nacelle-pylon wakes and the wake from the fuselage "blanket" the horizontal stabilizer, rendering the elevators ineffective and preventing the aircraft from recovering from the stall.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Aircraft with rear-mounted nacelles may also exhibit a loss of thrust.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] T-tail propeller aircraft are generally resistant to deep stalls, because the prop wash increases airflow over the wing root, but may be fitted with a precautionary vertical tail booster during flight testing, as happened with the A400M.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Brian Trubshaw gives a broad definition of deep stall as penetrating to such angles of attack ${\textstyle \alpha }$ that pitch control effectiveness is reduced by the wing and nacelle wakes.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] He also gives a definition that relates deep stall to a locked-in condition where recovery is impossible.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] This is a single value of ${\textstyle \alpha }$ , for a given aircraft configuration, where there is no pitching moment, i.e. a trim point.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Typical values both for the range of deep stall, as defined above, and the locked-in trim point are given for the Douglas DC-9 Series 10 by Schaufele.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] These values are from wind-tunnel tests for an early design.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The final design had no locked-in trim point, so recovery from the deep stall region was possible, as required to meet certification rules.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Normal stall beginning at the "g break" (sudden decrease of the vertical load factor) was at ${\textstyle \alpha =18^{\circ }}$ , deep stall started at about 30°, and the locked-in unrecoverable trim point was at 47°.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The very high ${\textstyle \alpha }$ for a deep stall locked-in condition occurs well beyond the normal stall but can be attained very rapidly, as the aircraft is unstable beyond the normal stall and requires immediate action to arrest it.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The loss of lift causes high sink rates, which, together with the low forward speed at the normal stall, give a high ${\textstyle \alpha }$ with little or no rotation of the aircraft.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] BAC 1-11 G-ASHG, during stall flight tests before the type was modified to prevent a locked-in deep-stall condition, descended at over 10,000 feet per minute (50 m/s) and struck the ground in a flat attitude moving only 70 feet (20 m) forward after initial impact.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Sketches showing how the wing wake blankets the tail may be misleading if they imply that deep stall requires a high body angle.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Taylor and Ray show how the aircraft attitude in the deep stall is relatively flat, even less than during the normal stall, with very high negative flight-path angles.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Effects similar to deep stall had been known to occur on some aircraft designs before the term was coined.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] A prototype Gloster Javelin (serial *WD808*) was lost in a crash on 11 June 1953 to a "locked-in" stall.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] However, Waterton states that the trimming tailplane was found to be the wrong way for recovery.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Low-speed handling tests were being done to assess a new wing.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Handley Page Victor *XL159* was lost to a "stable stall" on 23 March 1962.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] It had been clearing the fixed droop leading edge with the test being stall approach, landing configuration, C of G aft.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The brake parachute had not been streamed, as it might have hindered rear crew escape.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The name "deep stall" first came into widespread use after the crash of the prototype BAC 1-11 G-ASHG on 22 October 1963, which killed its crew.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] This led to changes to the aircraft, including the installation of a stick shaker (see below) to clearly warn the pilot of an impending stall.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Stick shakers are now a standard part of commercial airliners.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] On 3 April 1980, a prototype of the Canadair Challenger business jet crashed after initially entering a deep stall from 17,000 ft and having both engines flame-out.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] It recovered from the deep stall after deploying the anti-spin parachute but crashed after being unable to jettison the chute or relight the engines.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] One of the test pilots was unable to escape from the aircraft in time and was killed.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] On 26 July 1993, a Canadair CRJ-100 was lost in flight testing due to a deep stall.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] It has been reported that a Boeing 727 entered a deep stall in a flight test, but the pilot was able to rock the airplane to increasingly higher bank angles until the nose finally fell through and normal control response was recovered.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The crash of West Caribbean Airways Flight 708 in 2005 was also attributed to a deep stall.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] AirAsia Flight 8501 is yet another notable example of an unrecoverable stall.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The 2024 Saurya Airlines Bombardier CRJ200 crash has been attributed to a deep stall caused by slow speed and excessive rotation rate during takeoff.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Canard-configured aircraft are also at risk of getting into a deep stall.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Two Velocity aircraft crashed due to locked-in deep stalls.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Testing revealed that the addition of leading-edge cuffs to the outboard wing prevented the aircraft from getting into a deep stall.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The Piper Advanced Technologies PAT-1, N15PT, another canard-configured aircraft, also crashed in an accident attributed to a deep stall.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Wind-tunnel testing of the design at the NASA Langley Research Center showed that it was vulnerable to a deep stall.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Wing sweep and taper cause stalling at the tip of a wing before the root.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The position of a swept wing along the fuselage has to be such that the lift from the wing root, well forward of the aircraft center of gravity (c.g.), must be balanced by the wing tip, well aft of the c.g.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] If the tip stalls first the balance of the aircraft is upset causing dangerous nose pitch up.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Swept wings have to incorporate features which prevent pitch-up caused by premature tip stall.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] A swept wing has a higher lift coefficient on its outer panels than on the inner wing, causing them to reach their maximum lift capability first and to stall first.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] This is caused by the downwash pattern associated with swept/tapered wings.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] To delay tip stall the outboard wing is given washout to reduce its angle of attack.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The root can also be modified with a suitable leading-edge and airfoil section to make sure it stalls before the tip.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] However, when taken beyond stalling incidence the tips may still become fully stalled before the inner wing despite initial separation occurring inboard.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] This causes pitch-up after the stall and entry to a super-stall on those aircraft with super-stall characteristics.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Span-wise flow of the boundary layer is also present on swept wings and causes tip stall.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The amount of boundary layer air flowing outboard can be reduced by generating vortices with a leading-edge device such as a fence, notch, saw tooth or a set of vortex generators behind the leading edge.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Fixed-wing aircraft can be equipped with devices to prevent or postpone a stall or to make it less (or in some cases more) severe, or to make recovery easier.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Stall warning systems often involve inputs from a broad range of sensors and systems to include a dedicated angle of attack sensor.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Blockage, damage, or inoperation of stall and angle of attack (AOA) probes can lead to unreliability of the stall warning and cause the stick pusher, overspeed warning, autopilot, and yaw damper to malfunction.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] If a forward canard is used for pitch control, rather than an aft tail, the canard is designed to meet the airflow at a slightly greater angle of attack than the wing.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Therefore, when the aircraft pitch increases abnormally, the canard will usually stall first, causing the nose to drop and so preventing the wing from reaching its critical AOA.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Thus, the risk of main-wing stalling is greatly reduced.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] However, if the main wing stalls, recovery becomes difficult, as the canard is more deeply stalled, and angle of attack increases rapidly.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] If an aft tail is used, the wing is designed to stall before the tail.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] In this case, the wing can be flown at higher lift coefficient (closer to stall) to produce more overall lift.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Most military combat aircraft have an angle of attack indicator among the pilot's instruments, which lets the pilot know precisely how close to the stall point the aircraft is.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Modern airliner instrumentation may also measure angle of attack, although this information may not be directly displayed on the pilot's display, instead driving a stall warning indicator or giving performance information to the flight computer (for fly-by-wire systems).
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] As a wing stalls, aileron effectiveness is reduced, rendering the plane difficult to control and increasing the risk of a spin.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Post stall, steady flight beyond the stalling angle (where the coefficient of lift is largest) requires engine thrust to replace lift, as well as alternative controls to replace the loss of effectiveness of the ailerons.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Pugachev's cobra) are sometimes performed at airshows.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The highest angle of attack in sustained flight so far demonstrated was 70° in the X-31 at the Dryden Flight Research Center.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Sustained post-stall flight is a type of supermaneuverability.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Except for flight training, airplane testing, and aerobatics, a stall is usually an undesirable event.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Spoilers (sometimes called lift dumpers), however, are devices that are intentionally deployed to create a carefully controlled flow separation over part of an aircraft's wing to reduce the lift it generates, increase the drag, and allow the aircraft to descend more rapidly without gaining speed.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Spoilers are also deployed asymmetrically (one wing only) to enhance roll control.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Spoilers can also be used on aborted take-offs and after main wheel contact on landing to increase the aircraft's weight on its wheels for better braking action.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Unlike powered airplanes, which can control descent by increasing or decreasing thrust, gliders have to increase drag to increase the rate of descent.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] In high-performance gliders, spoiler deployment is extensively used to control the approach to landing.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Spoilers can also be thought of as "lift reducers" because they reduce the lift of the wing in which the spoiler resides.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] For example, an uncommanded roll to the left could be reversed by raising the right wing spoiler (or only a few of the spoilers present in large airliner wings).
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] This has the advantage of avoiding the need to increase lift in the wing that is dropping (which may bring that wing closer to stalling).
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] German aviator Otto Lilienthal died while flying in 1896 as the result of a stall.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Wilbur Wright encountered stalls for the first time in 1901, while flying his second glider.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] Awareness of Lilienthal's accident and Wilbur's experience motivated the Wright brothers to design their plane in "canard" configuration.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] This purportedly made recoveries from stalls easier and more gentle.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The design allegedly saved the brothers' lives more than once.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] However, canard configurations, without careful design, can actually make a stall unrecoverable.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] The aircraft engineer Juan de la Cierva worked on his "Autogiro" project to develop a rotary wing aircraft which, he hoped, would be unable to stall and which therefore would be safer than aeroplanes.
[src:axial-compressor/aerodynamic-stall] In developing the resulting "autogyro" aircraft, his solution of numerous engineering problems related to the rotary wing led to the development of the helicopter.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] An **afterburner** (or **reheat** in British English) is an additional combustion component used on some jet engines, mostly those on military supersonic aircraft.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Its purpose is to increase thrust, usually for supersonic flight, takeoff, and combat.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] The afterburning process injects additional fuel into a combustor ("burner") in the jet pipe behind (i.e., "after") the turbine, "reheating" the exhaust gas.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Afterburning significantly increases thrust and is used as an alternative to a larger, heavier engine.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] However, it increases fuel consumption and decreases fuel efficiency, which limits its use to short periods.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] This aircraft application of "reheat" contrasts with the meaning and implementation of "reheat" applicable to gas turbines driving electrical generators and which reduces fuel consumption.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Jet engines are referred to as operating *wet* when afterburning and *dry* when not.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] An engine producing maximum thrust wet is at *maximum power,* while an engine producing maximum thrust dry is at *military power*.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] The first jet engine with after-burner was the E variant of the Jumo 004.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Jet-engine thrust is an application of Newton's reaction principle, in which the engine generates thrust because it increases the momentum of the air passing through it.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Thrust depends on two things: the velocity of the exhaust gas and the mass of the gas exiting the nozzle.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] A jet engine can produce more thrust by either accelerating the gas to a higher velocity or ejecting a greater mass of gas from the engine.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Designing a basic turbojet engine around the second principle produces the turbofan engine, which creates slower gas, but more of it.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Turbofans are highly fuel efficient and can deliver high thrust for long periods of time, but the design tradeoff is a large size relative to the power output.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Generating increased power with a more compact engine for short periods can be achieved using an afterburner.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] The afterburner increases thrust primarily by accelerating the exhaust gas to a higher velocity.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] The following values and parameters are for an early jet engine, the Pratt & Whitney J57, stationary on the runway, and illustrate the high values of afterburner fuel flow, gas temperature and thrust compared to those for the engine operating within the temperature limitations for its turbine.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] The highest temperature in the engine (about 3,700 °F (2,040 °C) occurs in the combustion chamber, where fuel is burned (at an approximate rate of 8,520 lb/h (3,860 kg/h)) in a relatively small proportion of the air entering the engine.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] The combustion products have to be diluted with air from the compressor to bring the gas temperature down to a specific value, known as the Turbine Entry Temperature (TET) (1,570 °F (850 °C)), which gives the turbine an acceptable life.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Having to reduce the temperature of the combustion products by a large amount is one of the primary limitations on how much thrust can be generated (10,200 lbf (45,000 N)).
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] The gas temperature decreases as it passes through the turbine (to 1,013 °F (545 °C)).
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] The afterburner combustor reheats the gas, but to a much higher temperature (2,540 °F (1,390 °C)) than the TET (1,570 °F (850 °C)).
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] As a result of the temperature rise in the afterburner combustor, the gas is accelerated, firstly by the heat addition, known as Rayleigh flow, then by the nozzle to a higher exit velocity than that which occurs without the afterburner.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] The mass flow is also slightly increased by the addition of the afterburner fuel.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] The thrust with afterburning is 16,000 lbf (71,000 N).
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] The visible exhaust may show *shock diamonds*, which are caused by shock waves formed due to slight differences between ambient pressure and the exhaust pressure.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] This interaction causes oscillations in the exhaust jet diameter over a short distance and causes visible banding where pressure and temperature are highest.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Thrust may be increased by burning fuel in a turbofan's cold bypass air, instead of the mixed cold and hot flows as in most afterburning turbofans.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] An early augmented turbofan, the Pratt & Whitney TF30, used separate burning zones for the bypass and core flows with three of seven concentric spray rings in the bypass flow.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] In comparison, the afterburning Rolls-Royce Spey used a twenty chute mixer before the fuel manifolds.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Plenum chamber burning (PCB) was partially developed for the vectored thrust Bristol Siddeley BS100 engine for the Hawker Siddeley P.1154 until the program was cancelled in 1965.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] The cold bypass and hot core flows were split between two pairs of nozzles, front and rear, in the same manner as the Rolls-Royce Pegasus, and fuel was burned in the fan air before it left the front nozzles.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] It would have given greater thrust for take-off and supersonic performance in an aircraft similar to, but bigger than, the Hawker Siddeley Harrier.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Duct heating was used by Pratt & Whitney for their JTF17 turbofan proposal for the U.S.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Supersonic Transport Program in 1964 and a demonstrator engine was run.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] The duct heater used an annular combustor and would be used for takeoff, climb and cruise at Mach 2.7 with different amounts of augmentation depending on aircraft weight.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] A jet engine afterburner is an extended exhaust section containing extra fuel injectors.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Since the jet engine upstream (i.e., before the turbine) will use little of the oxygen it ingests, additional fuel can be burned after the gas flow has left the turbines.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] When the afterburner is turned on, fuel is injected and igniters are fired.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] The resulting combustion process increases the afterburner exit (nozzle entry) temperature, resulting in a significant increase in engine thrust.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] The resulting increase in afterburner exit volume flow is accommodated by increasing the throat area of the exit nozzle.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Otherwise, if pressure is not released, the gas can flow upstream and re-ignite, possibly causing a compressor stall (or fan surge in a turbofan application).
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Solar afterburners used on the F7U Cutlass, F-94 Starfire and F-89 Scorpion, had 2-position eyelid nozzles.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Modern designs incorporate not only variable-geometry (VG) nozzles but multiple stages of augmentation via separate spray bars.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] To a first order, the gross thrust ratio (afterburning/dry) is directly proportional to the root of the stagnation temperature ratio across the afterburner (i.e. exit/entry).
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Due to their high fuel consumption, afterburners are only used for short-duration, high-thrust requirements.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] These include heavy-weight or short-runway take-offs, assisting catapult launches from aircraft carriers, and during air combat.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] A notable exception is the Pratt & Whitney J58 engine used in the SR-71 Blackbird which used its afterburner for prolonged periods and was refueled in-flight as part of every reconnaissance mission.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] An afterburner has a limited life to match its intermittent use.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] The J58 was an exception with a continuous rating.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] This was achieved with thermal barrier coatings on the liner and flame holders and by cooling the liner and nozzle with compressor bleed air instead of turbine exhaust gas.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] In heat engines such as jet engines, efficiency is highest when combustion occurs at the highest pressure and temperature possible, and expanded down to ambient pressure (see Carnot cycle).
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Since the exhaust gas already has a reduced oxygen content, owing to previous combustion, and since the fuel is not burning in a highly compressed air column, the afterburner is generally inefficient in comparison to the main combustion process.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Afterburner efficiency also declines significantly if, as is usually the case, the inlet and tailpipe pressure decreases with increasing altitude.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] This limitation applies only to turbojets.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] In a military turbofan combat engine, the bypass air is added into the exhaust, thereby increasing the core and afterburner efficiency.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] In turbojets the gain is limited to 50%, whereas in a turbofan it depends on the bypass ratio and can be as much as 70%.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] However, as a counterexample, the SR-71 had reasonable efficiency at high altitude in afterburning ("wet") mode owing to its high speed (Mach 3.2) and correspondingly high pressure due to ram intake.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Afterburning has a significant influence upon engine cycle choice.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Lowering the fan pressure ratio decreases specific thrust (both dry and wet afterburning), but results in a lower temperature entering the afterburner.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Since the afterburning exit temperature is effectively fixed, the temperature rise across the unit increases, raising the afterburner fuel flow.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] The total fuel flow tends to increase faster than the net thrust, resulting in a higher specific fuel consumption (SFC).
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] However, the corresponding dry power SFC improves (i.e. lower specific thrust).
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] The high temperature ratio across the afterburner results in a good thrust boost.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] If the aircraft burns a large percentage of its fuel with the afterburner alight, it pays to select an engine cycle with a high specific thrust (i.e. high fan pressure ratio/low bypass ratio).
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] The resulting engine is relatively fuel efficient with afterburning (i.e.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Combat/Take-off), but thirsty in dry power.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] If, however, the afterburner is to be hardly used, a low specific thrust (low fan pressure ratio/high bypass ratio) cycle will be favored.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Such an engine has a good dry SFC, but a poor afterburning SFC at Combat/Take-off.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Often the engine designer is faced with a compromise between these two extremes.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] The Caproni Campini C.C.2 motorjet, designed by the Italian engineer Secondo Campini, was the first aircraft to incorporate an afterburner.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] The first flight of a C.C.2, with its afterburners operating, took place on 11 April 1941.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Early British afterburner ("reheat") work included flight tests on a Rolls-Royce W2/B23 in a Gloster Meteor I in late 1944 and ground tests on a Power Jets W2/700 engine in mid-1945.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] This engine was destined for the Miles M.52 supersonic aircraft project.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Early American research on the concept was done by NACA, in Cleveland, Ohio, leading to the publication of the paper "Theoretical Investigation of Thrust Augmentation of Turbojet Engines by Tail-pipe Burning" in January 1947.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] American work on afterburners in 1948 resulted in installations on early straight-wing jets such as the Pirate, Starfire and Scorpion.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] The new Pratt & Whitney J48 turbojet, at 8,000 lbf (36 kN) thrust with afterburners, would power the Grumman swept-wing fighter F9F-6, which was about to go into production.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Other new Navy fighters with afterburners included the Chance Vought F7U-3 Cutlass, powered by two 6,000 lbf (27 kN) thrust Westinghouse J46 engines.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] In the 1950s, several large afterburning engines were developed, such as the Orenda Iroquois and the British de Havilland Gyron and Rolls-Royce Avon RB.146 variants.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] The Avon and its variants powered the English Electric Lightning, the first supersonic aircraft in RAF service.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] The Bristol-Siddeley/Rolls-Royce Olympus was fitted with afterburners for use with the BAC TSR-2.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] This system was designed and developed jointly by Bristol-Siddeley and Solar of San Diego.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] The afterburner system for the Concorde was developed by Snecma.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Afterburners are generally used only in military aircraft, and are considered standard equipment on fighter aircraft.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] The handful of civilian planes that have used them include some NASA research aircraft, the Tupolev Tu-144, Concorde and the White Knight of Scaled Composites.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Concorde flew long distances at supersonic speeds.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Sustained high speeds would be impossible with the high fuel consumption of afterburner, and the plane used afterburners at takeoff and to minimize time spent in the high-drag transonic flight regime.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Supersonic flight without afterburners is referred to as supercruise.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] A turbojet engine equipped with an afterburner is called an "afterburning turbojet", whereas a turbofan engine similarly equipped is sometimes called an "augmented turbofan".
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] A "dump-and-burn" is an airshow display feature where fuel is jettisoned, then intentionally ignited using the afterburner.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] A spectacular flame combined with high speed makes this a popular display for airshows, or as a finale to fireworks.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Fuel dumping is used primarily to reduce the weight of an aircraft to avoid a heavy, high-speed landing.
[src:axial-compressor/afterburner] Other than for safety or emergency reasons, fuel dumping does not have a practical use.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] There are various types of air conditioners.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] In hot weather, air conditioning can prevent heat stroke, dehydration due to excessive sweating, electrolyte imbalance, kidney failure, and other issues due to hyperthermia.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] An estimated 190,000 heat-related deaths are averted annually owing to air conditioning.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Air conditioners increase productivity in hot climates, and historians rank air conditioning as a key factor that shaped postwar metropolitan growth, alongside highways, automobiles, shopping malls, and suburban housing.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] As of 2022, air conditioning used about 7% of global electricity and emitted 3% of greenhouse gas.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Air conditioners, which typically use vapor-compression refrigeration, range in size from small units used in vehicles or single rooms to massive units that can cool large buildings.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Air source heat pumps, which can be used for heating as well as cooling, are becoming increasingly common in cooler climates.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] According to the International Energy Agency (IEA) 1.6 billion air conditioning units were used globally in 2016.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The United Nations has called for the technology to be made more sustainable to mitigate climate change and for the use of alternatives, such as passive cooling, evaporative cooling, selective shading, windcatchers, and thermal insulation.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Air conditioning dates back to prehistory.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Double-walled living quarters, with a gap between the two walls to encourage air flow, were found in the ancient city of Hamoukar, in modern Syria.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Ancient Egyptian buildings also used a wide variety of passive air-conditioning techniques.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] These became widespread from the Iberian Peninsula through North Africa, the Middle East, and Northern India.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Passive techniques remained widespread until the 20th century when they fell out of fashion and were replaced by powered air conditioning.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Using information from engineering studies of traditional buildings, passive techniques are being revived and modified for 21st-century architectural designs.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Air conditioners allow the building's indoor environment to remain relatively constant, largely independent of changes in external weather conditions and internal heat loads.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] They also enable deep plan buildings to be created and have allowed people to live comfortably in hotter parts of the world.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] In 1558, Giambattista della Porta described a method of chilling ice to temperatures far below its freezing point by mixing it with potassium nitrate (then called "nitre") in his popular science book *Natural Magic*.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] In 1620, Cornelis Drebbel demonstrated "Turning Summer into Winter" for James I of England, chilling part of the Great Hall of Westminster Abbey with an apparatus of troughs and vats.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] In 1758, Benjamin Franklin and John Hadley, a chemistry professor at the University of Cambridge, conducted experiments applying the principle of evaporation as a means to cool an object rapidly.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Franklin and Hadley confirmed that the evaporation of highly volatile liquids (such as alcohol and ether) could be used to drive down the temperature of an object past the freezing point of water.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] They experimented with the bulb of a mercury-in-glass thermometer as their object.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] They used a bellows to speed up the evaporation.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] They lowered the temperature of the thermometer bulb down to −14 °C (7 °F) while the ambient temperature was 18 °C (64 °F).
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Franklin noted that soon after they passed the freezing point of water 0 °C (32 °F), a thin film of ice formed on the surface of the thermometer's bulb and that the ice mass was about 6 mm (1⁄4 in) thick when they stopped the experiment upon reaching −14 °C (7 °F).
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The 19th century included many developments in compression technology.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] In 1820, English scientist and inventor Michael Faraday discovered that compressing and liquefying ammonia could chill air when the liquefied ammonia was allowed to evaporate.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] In 1842, Florida physician John Gorrie used compressor technology to create ice, which he used to cool air for his patients in his hospital in Apalachicola, Florida.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] He hoped to eventually use his ice-making machine to regulate the temperature of buildings.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] He envisioned centralized air conditioning that could cool entire cities.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Gorrie was granted a patent in 1851, but following the death of his main backer, he was not able to realize his invention.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] In 1851, James Harrison created the first mechanical ice-making machine in Geelong, Australia, and was granted a patent for an ether vapor-compression refrigeration system in 1855 that produced three tons of ice per day.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] In 1860, Harrison established a second ice company.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] He later entered the debate over competing against the American advantage of ice-refrigerated beef sales to the United Kingdom.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] This innovation made the systems more compact and suitable for urban environments.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] By 1896, his factory produced 'dry air cooling apparatuses' specifically designed for the cooling and dehumidification of hospitals, theaters, large public halls, and even residential rooms, several years before the widespread commercialization of modern air conditioning.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] This system operated by using an electric motor-driven ammonia compressor to chill a secondary refrigerant, typically brine (salt water).
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] This cold brine was circulated through pipes to a 'dry air cooling unit' (a precursor to the modern air handler), where a fan forced ambient air over the chilled coils.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] This process not only lowered the temperature but also dehumidified the air by condensing moisture on the cold surfaces.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Electricity made the development of effective units possible.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Carrier built what is considered the first modern electrical air conditioning unit.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] In 1902, he installed his first air-conditioning system in the Sackett-Wilhelms Lithographing & Publishing Company in Brooklyn, New York.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] He patented "air conditioning" in 1906, and by 1914, the first domestic (or "residential") air conditioner was installed.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] His invention controlled both the temperature and humidity, which helped maintain consistent paper dimensions and ink alignment at the printing plant.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Later, together with six other employees, Carrier formed The Carrier Air Conditioning Company of America, a business that in 2020, employed 53,000 people and was valued at $18.6 billion.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Cramer of Charlotte, North Carolina, was exploring ways to add moisture to the air in his textile mill.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Cramer coined the term "air conditioning" in a patent claim which he filed that year, where he suggested that air conditioning was analogous to "water conditioning", then a well-known process for making textiles easier to process.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] He combined moisture with ventilation to "condition" and change the air in the factories, thus controlling the humidity that is necessary in textile plants.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Willis Carrier adopted the term and incorporated it into the name of his company.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Domestic air conditioning soon took off.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] In 1914, the first domestic air conditioning was installed in Minneapolis in the home of Charles Gilbert Gates.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] It is, however, possible that the considerable device (c.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Sherman developed what would become the most common type of individual room air conditioner: one designed to sit on a window ledge.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The units went on sale in 1932 at US$10,000 to $50,000 (the equivalent of $200,000 to $1,200,000 in 2025.) A year later, the first air conditioning systems for cars were offered for sale.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Chrysler Motors introduced the first practical semi-portable air conditioning unit in 1935, and Packard became the first automobile manufacturer to offer an air conditioning unit in its cars in 1939.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Innovations in the latter half of the 20th century allowed more ubiquitous air conditioner use.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] In 1945, Robert Sherman of Lynn, Massachusetts, invented a portable, in-window air conditioner that cooled, heated, humidified, dehumidified, and filtered the air.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The first inverter air conditioners were released in 1980–1981.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] In 1954, Ned Cole, a 1939 architecture graduate from the University of Texas at Austin, developed the first experimental "suburb" with inbuilt air conditioning in each house.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] In addition, researchers from UT's Health Service and Psychology Department studied the effects on the "artificially cooled humans." One of the more amusing discoveries was that each family reported being troubled with scorpions, the leading theory being that scorpions sought cool, shady places.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Other reported changes in lifestyle were that mothers baked more, families ate heavier foods, and they were more apt to choose hot drinks.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Air conditioner adoption tends to increase above around $10,000 (circa 2021) annual household income in warmer areas.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Global GDP growth explains around 85% of increased air condition adoption by 2050, while the remaining 15% can be explained by climate change.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The urban heat island effect was first scientifically noted by Luke Howard in the 1810s, who described London being several degrees warmer than its rural surroundings at night.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The phenomenon gained attention in the late 1960s, mainly in Japan and North America.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] From the late 1980s to early 2010s, studies began to link air conditioners to the urban heat island effect.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The phenomenon was observed in various cities such as Tokyo and Houston.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] As of 2016, an estimated 1.6 billion air conditioning units were used worldwide, with over half of them in China and the United States, and with a total cooling capacity of 11,675 gigawatts.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The International Energy Agency predicted in 2018 that the number of air conditioning units would grow to around 4 billion units by 2050 and that the total cooling capacity would grow to around 23,000 GW, with the biggest increases in India and China.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Between 1995 and 2004, the proportion of urban households in China with air conditioners increased from 8% to 70%.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Between 2010 and 2023, air conditioner use in India tripled to 24 units per 100 households, with the most ownership in Haryana, Chandigarh, Rajasthan, and Delhi and the least in Meghalaya, Tripura, Manipur, and Himachal Pradesh.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] As of 2015, nearly 100 million homes in the United States, or about 87% of US households, had air conditioning systems.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] In 2019, it was estimated that 90% of new single-family homes constructed in the US included air conditioning, ranging from 99% in the South to 62% in the West.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] As of 2025, roughly half of homes in Italy, 40 percent of homes in Spain, and 20 to 25 percent of homes in France had air conditioning.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Cooling in traditional air conditioner systems is accomplished using the vapor-compression cycle, which uses a refrigerant's forced circulation and phase change between gas and liquid to transfer heat.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The vapor-compression cycle can occur within a unitary, or packaged piece of equipment, or within a chiller that is connected to terminal cooling equipment (such as a fan coil unit in an air handler) on its evaporator side and heat rejection equipment such as a cooling tower on its condenser side.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] An air source heat pump shares many components with an air conditioning system, but includes a reversing valve, which allows the unit to be used to heat as well as cool a space.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Air conditioning equipment will reduce the absolute humidity of the air processed by the system if the surface of the evaporator coil is significantly cooler than the dew point of the surrounding air.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] An air conditioner designed for an occupied space will typically achieve a 30% to 60% relative humidity in the occupied space.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Most modern air-conditioning systems feature a dehumidification mode, in which the compressor runs.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] At the same time, the fan is slowed to reduce the evaporator temperature and condense more water.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Free cooling can sometimes be selected when the external air is cooler than the internal air.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] In this case, the compressor does not need to be used, resulting in high cooling efficiencies for these times.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] This may also be combined with seasonal thermal energy storage.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Some air conditioning systems can reverse the refrigeration cycle and act as an air source heat pump, thus heating instead of cooling the indoor environment.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] They are also commonly referred to as "reverse cycle air conditioners".
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The heat pump is significantly more energy-efficient than electric resistance heating, because it moves energy from air or groundwater to the heated space and the heat from purchased electrical energy.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] When the heat pump is in heating mode, the indoor evaporator coil switches roles and becomes the condenser coil, producing heat and the outdoor condenser unit also switches roles to serve as the evaporator and discharges cold air (colder than the ambient outdoor air).
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Most air source heat pumps become less efficient in outdoor temperatures lower than 4 °C or 40 °F.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] This is partly because ice forms on the outdoor unit's heat exchanger coil, which blocks air flow over the coil.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] To compensate for this, the heat pump system must temporarily switch back into the regular air conditioning mode to switch the outdoor evaporator coil back to being the condenser coil, so it can heat up and defrost.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Therefore, some heat pump systems will have electric resistance heating in the indoor air path that is activated only in this mode to compensate for the temporary indoor air cooling, which would otherwise be uncomfortable in the winter.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Newer models have improved cold-weather performance, with efficient heating capacity down to −14 °F (−26 °C).
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] However, there is always a chance that the humidity that condenses on the heat exchanger of the outdoor unit could freeze, even in models that have improved cold-weather performance, requiring a defrosting cycle to be performed.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] In this case, the heat pump is used efficiently during milder temperatures, and the system is switched to the conventional heat source when the outdoor temperature is lower.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The coefficient of performance (COP) of an air conditioning system is a ratio of useful heating or cooling provided to the work required.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Higher COPs equate to lower operating costs.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The COP usually exceeds 1; however, the exact value is highly dependent on operating conditions, especially absolute temperature and relative temperature between sink and system, and is often graphed or averaged against expected conditions.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Air conditioner equipment power in the U.S. is often described in terms of "tons of refrigeration", with each approximately equal to the cooling power of one short ton (2,000 pounds (910 kg) of ice melting in a 24-hour period.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The value is equal to 12,000 BTUIT per hour, or 3,517 watts.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Residential central air systems are usually from 1 to 5 tons (3.5 to 18 kW) in capacity.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The efficiency of air conditioners is often rated by the seasonal energy efficiency ratio (SEER), which is defined by the Air Conditioning, Heating and Refrigeration Institute in its 2008 standard AHRI 210/240, *Performance Rating of Unitary Air-Conditioning and Air-Source Heat Pump Equipment*.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] A similar standard is the European seasonal energy efficiency ratio (ESEER).
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Efficiency is strongly affected by the humidity of the air to be cooled.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Dehumidifying the air before attempting to cool it can reduce subsequent cooling costs by as much as 90 percent.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Thus, reducing dehumidifying costs can materially affect overall air conditioning costs.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] This type of controller uses an infrared LED to relay commands from a remote control to the air conditioner.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The output of the infrared LED (like that of any infrared remote) is invisible to the human eye because its wavelength is beyond the range of visible light (940 nm).
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] This system is commonly used on mini-split air conditioners because it is simple and portable.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Some window and ducted central air conditioners uses it as well.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] A wired controller, also called a "wired thermostat," is a device that controls an air conditioner by switching heating or cooling on or off.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] It uses different sensors to measure temperatures and actuate control operations.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Mechanical thermostats commonly use bimetallic strips, converting a temperature change into mechanical displacement, to actuate control of the air conditioner.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Electronic thermostats, instead, use a thermistor or other semiconductor sensor, processing temperature change as electronic signals to control the air conditioner.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] These controllers are usually used in apartments, hospitals, offices and hotel rooms, because they are permanently installed into a wall and hard-wired directly into the air conditioner unit, eliminating the need for batteries.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Ductless systems (often mini-split, though there are now ducted mini-split) typically supply conditioned and heated air to a single or a few rooms of a building, without ducts and in a decentralized manner.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Multi-zone or multi-split systems are a common application of ductless systems and allow up to eight rooms (zones or locations) to be conditioned independently from each other, each with its indoor unit and simultaneously from a single outdoor unit.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The first mini-split system was sold in 1961 by Toshiba in Japan, and the first wall-mounted mini-split air conditioner was sold in 1968 in Japan by Mitsubishi Electric, where small home sizes motivated their development.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The Mitsubishi model was the first air conditioner with a cross-flow fan.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] In 1969, the first mini-split air conditioner was sold in the US.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Multi-zone ductless systems were invented by Daikin in 1973, and variable refrigerant flow systems (which can be thought of as larger multi-split systems) were also invented by Daikin in 1982.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The outdoor and indoor units can be spread across the building.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Variable refrigerant flow indoor units can also be turned off individually in unused spaces.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The lower start-up power of VRF's DC inverter compressors and their inherent DC power requirements also allow VRF solar-powered heat pumps to be run using DC-providing solar panels.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Split-system central air conditioners consist of two heat exchangers, an outside unit (the condenser) from which heat is rejected to the environment and an internal heat exchanger (the evaporator, or Fan Coil Unit, FCU) with the piped refrigerant being circulated between the two.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The FCU is then connected to the spaces to be cooled by ventilation ducts.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Floor standing air conditioners are similar to this type of air conditioner but sit within spaces that need cooling.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The chilled water is cooled by chillers in the plant, which uses a refrigeration cycle to cool water, often transferring its heat to the atmosphere even in liquid-cooled chillers through the use of cooling towers.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] A portable system has an indoor unit on wheels connected to an outdoor unit via flexible pipes, similar to a permanently fixed installed unit (such as a ductless split air conditioner).
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Hose systems, which can be *monoblock* or *air-to-air*, are vented to the outside via air ducts.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The *monoblock* type collects the water in a bucket or tray and stops when full.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The *air-to-air* type re-evaporates the water, discharges it through the ducted hose, and can run continuously.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Many but not all portable units draw indoor air and expel it outdoors through a single duct, negatively impacting their overall cooling efficiency.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Many portable air conditioners come with heat as well as a dehumidification function.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The packaged terminal air conditioner (PTAC), through-the-wall, and window air conditioners are similar.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] These units are installed on a window frame or on a wall opening.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The unit usually has an internal partition separating its indoor and outdoor sides, which contain the unit's condenser and evaporator, respectively.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] PTAC systems may be adapted to provide heating in cold weather, either directly by using an electric strip, gas, or other heaters, or by reversing the refrigerant flow to heat the interior and draw heat from the exterior air, converting the air conditioner into a heat pump.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] They may be installed in a wall opening with the help of a special sleeve on the wall and a custom grill that is flush with the wall and window air conditioners can also be installed in a window, but without a custom grill.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Packaged air conditioners (also known as self-contained units) are central systems that integrate into a single housing all the components of a split central system, and deliver air, possibly through ducts, to the spaces to be cooled.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Depending on their construction the units may be kept outdoors or indoors; draw the air to be conditioned from inside or outside a building and be water or air-cooled.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Often, outdoor units are air-cooled while indoor units are liquid-cooled using a cooling tower.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] This compressor consists of a crankcase, crankshaft, piston rod, piston, piston ring, cylinder head and valves.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] This compressor uses two interleaving scrolls to compress the refrigerant. it consists of one fixed and one orbiting scrolls.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] This type of compressor is more efficient because it has 70 percent less moving parts than a reciprocating compressor.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] This compressor use two very closely meshing spiral rotors to compress the gas.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The gas enters at the suction side and moves through the threads as the screws rotate.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The meshing rotors force the gas through the compressor, and the gas exits at the end of the screws.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The working area is the inter-lobe volume between the male and female rotors.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] It is larger at the intake end, and decreases along the length of the rotors until the exhaust port.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] This change in volume is the compression.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] There are several ways to modulate the cooling capacity in refrigeration or air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The most common in air conditioning are: on-off cycling, hot gas bypass, use or not of liquid injection, manifold configurations of multiple compressors, mechanical modulation (also called digital), and inverter technology.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Hot gas bypass involves injecting a quantity of gas from discharge to the suction side.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The compressor will keep operating at the same speed, but due to the bypass, the refrigerant mass flow circulating with the system is reduced, and thus the cooling capacity is also reduced.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] This naturally causes the compressor to run uselessly during the periods when the bypass is operating.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The turn down capacity varies between 0 and 100%.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Several compressors can be installed in the system to provide the peak cooling capacity.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Each compressor can run or not in order to stage the cooling capacity of the unit.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The turn down capacity is either 0/33/66 or 100% for a trio configuration and either 0/50 or 100% for a tandem.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] This internal mechanical capacity modulation is based on periodic compression process with a control valve, the two scroll set move apart stopping the compression for a given time period.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] This method varies refrigerant flow by changing the average time of compression, but not the actual speed of the motor.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Despite an excellent turndown ratio – from 10 to 100% of the cooling capacity, mechanically modulated scrolls have high energy consumption as the motor continuously runs.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] This system uses a variable-frequency drive (also called an Inverter) to control the speed of the compressor.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The refrigerant flow rate is changed by the change in the speed of the compressor.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The turn down ratio depends on the system configuration and manufacturer.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] It modulates from 15 or 25% up to 100% at full capacity with a single inverter from 12 to 100% with a hybrid tandem.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] This method is the most efficient way to modulate an air conditioner's capacity.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] It is up to 58% more efficient than a fixed speed system.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Heat waves are the most lethal type of weather phenomenon in the United States.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] A 2020 study found that areas with lower use of air conditioning correlated with higher rates of heat-related mortality and hospitalizations.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The August 2003 France heatwave resulted in approximately 15,000 deaths, where 80% of the victims were over 75 years old.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] In response, the French government required all retirement homes to have at least one air-conditioned room at 25 °C (77 °F) per floor during heatwaves.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] A 2021 report estimated that around 345,000 people aged 65 and older died in 2019 from the heat, which is preventable with air conditioning.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Air conditioning (including filtration, humidification, cooling and disinfection) can be used to provide a clean, safe, hypoallergenic atmosphere in hospital operating rooms and other environments where proper atmosphere is critical to patient safety and well-being.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] It is sometimes recommended for home use by people with allergies, especially mold.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] However, poorly maintained water cooling towers can promote the growth and spread of microorganisms such as *Legionella pneumophila*, the infectious agent responsible for Legionnaires' disease.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] As long as the cooling tower is kept clean (usually by means of a chlorine treatment), these health hazards can be avoided or reduced.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The state of New York has codified requirements for registration, maintenance, and testing of cooling towers to protect against Legionella.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] First designed to benefit targeted industries such as the press as well as large factories, the invention quickly spread to public agencies and administrations with studies with claims of increased productivity close to 24% in places equipped with air conditioning.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Air conditioning contributed to the economic development of the American South after the 1950s by enabling industrial activities in hot climates and supporting the expansion of white-collar work in cooled office spaces.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] It also influenced urban sprawl and commuting patterns, as air-conditioned vehicles made suburban development more viable.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Historians rank air conditioning among key factors shaping postwar metropolitan growth, alongside highways, automobiles, shopping malls, and suburban housing.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Air conditioning caused various shifts in demography, notably that of the United States starting from the 1970s.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] In the US, the birth rate was lower in the spring than during other seasons until the 1970s but this difference then declined since then.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] As of 2007, the Sun Belt contained 30% of the total US population while it was inhabited by 24% of Americans at the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Moreover, the summer mortality rate in the US, which had been higher in regions subject to a heat wave during the summer, also evened out.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The spread of the use of air conditioning acts as a main driver for the growth of global demand of electricity.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] A 2020 survey found that an estimated 88% of all US households use AC, increasing to 93% when solely looking at homes built between 2010 and 2020.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Air conditioning used about 7% of global electricity in 2022, and emitted 3% of greenhouse gas.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] There is some push to increase the energy efficiency of air conditioners.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP) and the IEA found that if air conditioners could be twice as effective as now, 460 billion tons of GHG could be cut over 40 years.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The UNEP and IEA also recommended legislation to decrease the use of hydrofluorocarbons, better building insulation, and more sustainable temperature-controlled food supply chains going forward.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Refrigerants have also caused and continue to cause serious environmental issues, including ozone depletion and climate change, as several countries have not yet ratified the Kigali Amendment to reduce the consumption and production of hydrofluorocarbons.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] CFCs and HCFCs refrigerants such as R-12 and R-22, respectively, used within air conditioners have caused damage to the ozone layer, and hydrofluorocarbon refrigerants such as R-410A and R-404A, which were designed to replace CFCs and HCFCs, are instead exacerbating climate change.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Both issues happen due to the venting of refrigerant to the atmosphere, such as during repairs.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] HFO refrigerants, used in some if not most new equipment, solve both issues with an ozone damage potential (ODP) of zero and a much lower global warming potential (GWP) in the single or double digits vs. the three or four digits of hydrofluorocarbons.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Hydrofluorocarbons would have raised global temperatures by around 0.3–0.5 °C (0.5–0.9 °F) by 2100 without the Kigali Amendment.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] With the Kigali Amendment, the increase of global temperatures by 2100 due to hydrofluorocarbons is predicted to be around 0.06 °C (0.1 °F).
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Air conditioning units also contribute to pollution as they are difficult to disassemble or repair.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Separating metal and plastic at the end of a unit's life cycle is also costly and not practical, meaning units are frequently disposed of.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Several journalists say it is an *air conditioning paradox* that arises from the usage of air conditioners to adapt to the effects of climate change, leading to higher energy consumption and heat generation as a byproduct, thereby exacerbating the problem.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Alternatives are currently being explored by governments and researchers, such as more energy-efficient systems, passive cooling techniques, and the development of low-GWP refrigerants.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] However, balancing the demand for cooling with the need to reduce carbon footprints remains a complex and pressing issue.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] As renewable energy becomes cheaper and more popular, the energy source of air conditioners is shifting towards more renewable energy sources.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The danger of high-GWP refrigerants, such as HFCs, escaping into the atmosphere and trapping heat can be mitigated through development of low-GWP refrigerants.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Socioeconomic groups with an annual household income below around $10,000 (circa 2021) tend to have a low rate of air conditioning adoption, which worsens heat-related mortality.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The lack of cooling can be hazardous, as areas with lower use of air conditioning correlate with higher rates of heat-related mortality and hospitalizations.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Premature mortality in New York City is projected to grow by between 47% and 95% in 30 years, with lower-income and vulnerable populations most at risk.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Studies on the correlation between heat-related mortality and hospitalizations and living in low socioeconomic locations can be traced in Phoenix, Arizona; Hong Kong; China; Japan; and Italy.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Costs of health care can act as another barrier: the lack of private health insurance during a 2009 heat wave in Australia was associated with heat-related hospitalization.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] A study examining the US cities of Chicago, Detroit, Minneapolis, and Pittsburgh found that black households were half as likely to have central air conditioning units when compared to their white counterparts.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Especially in cities, redlining and other historical practices mean that racial disparities are also played out in heat islands, increasing temperatures in certain parts of the city.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] This is due to heat-absorbing building materials and pavements and lack of vegetation and shade coverage.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] There have been initiatives that provide cooling solutions to low-income communities, such as public cooling spaces.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Cooling has allowed for growth of indoor home space and has encouraged people, including children, to stay indoors more often.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] It has also created uniformity of different geographical areas and climate zones.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Alternatives to continual air conditioning include passive cooling, passive solar cooling, natural ventilation, operating shades to reduce solar gain, using trees, architectural shades, windows (and using window coatings) to reduce solar gain.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Buildings designed with passive air conditioning are generally less expensive to construct and maintain than buildings with conventional HVAC systems with lower energy demands.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] While tens of air changes per hour, and cooling of tens of degrees, can be achieved with passive methods, site-specific microclimate must be taken into account, complicating building design.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Many techniques can be used to increase comfort and reduce the temperature in buildings.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] These include evaporative cooling, selective shading, wind, thermal convection, and heat storage.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Passive ventilation is the process of supplying air to and removing air from an indoor space without using mechanical systems.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] It refers to the flow of external air to an indoor space as a result of pressure differences arising from natural forces.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] There are two types of natural ventilation occurring in buildings: *wind driven ventilation* and *buoyancy-driven ventilation*.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Wind driven ventilation arises from the different pressures created by wind around a building or structure, and openings being formed on the perimeter which then permit flow through the building.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Buoyancy-driven ventilation occurs as a result of the directional buoyancy force that results from temperature differences between the interior and exterior.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Since the internal heat gains which create temperature differences between the interior and exterior are created by natural processes, including the heat from people, and wind effects are variable, naturally ventilated buildings are sometimes called "breathing buildings".
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Natural solutions do not require energy for cooling purposes, and are therefore a very attractive solution.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Many ways to achieve this have been explored.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The structure of a building can help dissipate heat.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] For example, in Zimbabwe, Eastgate Development cut its energy use by 90% by utilizing termite mound inspired structures.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Coverage of windows can help reduce internal heat gain from sunlight.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Department of Energy estimates that window awnings can lower internal heat gain from sunlight by up to 77%.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The coating of roofs have also seen great success.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] In the United States, painting roofs white has been shown to lower roof temperatures by as much as 30 °C.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Meanwhile, in China, a project involving the installation of green roofs — roofs covered with vegetation — not only reduced the cooling demands of buildings, but also lowered the average land surface temperature in the area by 0.91 °C.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Planting trees can also help mitigate the heat island effect.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] A study in Europe discovered that tree cover can reduce land surface temperatures in cities by as much as 12 °C during the summer.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] In the United States, another study found that when tree cover reaches 40%, ground-level temperatures were lowered by nearly 6 °C.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Passive cooling is a building design approach that focuses on heat gain control and heat dissipation in a building in order to improve the indoor thermal comfort with low or no energy consumption.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] This approach works either by preventing heat from entering the interior (heat gain prevention) or by removing heat from the building (natural cooling).
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Natural cooling utilizes on-site energy, available from the natural environment, combined with the architectural design of building components (e.g. building envelope), rather than mechanical systems to dissipate heat.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Therefore, natural cooling depends not only on the architectural design of the building but on how the site's natural resources are used as heat sinks (i.e. everything that absorbs or dissipates heat).
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Examples of on-site heat sinks are the upper atmosphere (night sky), the outdoor air (wind), and the earth/soil.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Passive cooling is an important tool for design of buildings for climate change adaptation – reducing dependency on energy-intensive air conditioning in warming environments.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Passive daytime radiative cooling (PDRC) surfaces reflect incoming solar radiation and heat back into outer space through the infrared window for cooling during the daytime.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Daytime radiative cooling became possible with the ability to suppress solar heating using photonic structures, which emerged through a study by Raman et al.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] PDRCs can come in a variety of forms, including paint coatings and films, that are designed to be high in solar reflectance and thermal emittance.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] PDRC applications on building roofs and envelopes have demonstrated significant decreases in energy consumption and costs.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] In suburban single-family residential areas, PDRC application on roofs can potentially lower energy costs by 26% to 46%.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] PDRCs are predicted to show a market size of ~$27 billion for indoor space cooling by 2025 and have undergone a surge in research and development since the 2010s.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Hand fans have existed since prehistory.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Large human-powered fans built into buildings include the punkah.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] The Chinese inventor Ding Huan (1st century CE) of the Han dynasty invented a rotary fan for air conditioning, with seven wheels 3 m (10 ft) in diameter and manually powered by prisoners.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] 712–762) of the Tang dynasty (618–907) had the Cool Hall (*Liang Dian* 涼殿) built in the imperial palace, which the *Tang Yulin* describes as having water-powered fan wheels for air conditioning as well as rising jet streams of water from fountains.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] During the subsequent Song dynasty (960–1279), written sources mentioned the air conditioning rotary fan as even more widely used.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] In areas that are cold at night or in winter, heat storage is used.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Heat may be stored in earth or masonry; air is drawn past the masonry to heat or cool it.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] In areas that are below freezing at night in winter, snow and ice can be collected and stored in ice houses for later use in cooling.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] This technique is over 3,700 years old in the Middle East.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Harvesting outdoor ice during winter and transporting and storing for use in summer was practiced by wealthy Europeans in the early 1600s, and became popular in Europe and the Americas towards the end of the 1600s.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] This practice was replaced by mechanical compression-cycle icemakers.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] In dry, hot climates, the evaporative cooling effect may be used by placing water at the air intake, such that the draft draws air over water and then into the house.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] For this reason, it is sometimes said that the fountain, in the architecture of hot, arid climates, is like the fireplace in the architecture of cold climates.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Evaporative cooling also makes the air more humid, which can be beneficial in a dry desert climate.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] Evaporative coolers tend to feel as if they are not working during times of high humidity, when there is not much dry air with which the coolers can work to make the air as cool as possible for dwelling occupants.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] There is a longstanding political controversy about air conditioning.
[src:axial-compressor/air-conditioning] In the nations of Europe where the technology is relatively unadopted, the strongest opposition generally originates from environmentalists, European federalists, and left-wing parties, while supporters tend to be from the political right.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] An **air-start system** is a power source used to provide the initial rotation to start large diesel engines and gas turbines.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] Compared to a gasoline (petrol) engine, a diesel engine has a very high compression ratio, an essential design feature, as it is the heat of compression that ignites the fuel.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] An electric starter with sufficient power to turn a large diesel engine would itself be so large as to be impractical so there is a need for an alternative system.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] An air start system has three main components along with various safety components, namely the air start injector, the distributor and the air receivers.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] When the system is initiated, starting air from the receivers is distributed by the distributor unit to each respective air start valve according to the firing order of the engine’s cylinders.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] Safety components include flame traps, to prevent air line explosions, a turning gear interlock which ensures that air-start cannot be initiated when the turning gear is engaged, relief valves and isolation valves, as well as drain valves at certain points along the system.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] Control components include the control valves and remote air-start valves.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] A direct start system as used on a marine slow-speed diesel is required to have up to 12 starts on a non-reversing engine or 6 starts on a reversible, or geared, engine.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] When starting the engine, compressed air is admitted to whichever cylinder has a piston just over top dead center, forcing it downward.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] As the engine starts to turn, the air-start valve on the next cylinder in line opens to continue the rotation.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] After several rotations, fuel is injected into the cylinders, the engine starts running and the air is cut off.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] To further complicate matters, a large engine is usually "blown over" first with zero fuel settings and the indicator cocks open, to prove that the engine is clear of any water build up and that everything is free to turn.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] After a successful blow ahead and a blow astern, the indicator cocks are closed on all the cylinders, and then the engine can be started on fuel.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] Significant complexity is added to the engine by using an air-start system, as the cylinder head must have an extra valve in each cylinder to admit the air in for starting, plus the required control systems.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] This added complexity and cost limits the use of air-starters to very large and expensive reciprocating engines.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] Another method of air-starting an internal combustion engine is by using compressed air or gas to drive a fluid motor in place of an electric motor.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] They can be used to start engines from 5 to 320 liters in size and if more starting power is necessary two or more motors can be used.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] Starters of this type are used in place of electric motors because of their lighter weight and higher reliability.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] They can also outlast an electric starter by a factor of three and are easier to rebuild.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] Engines operating in underground mining activities tend to operate on this type of starter system to reduce the risk of an electrical system igniting flammable material.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] All vane type air starters should have a lubricator installed to insure long-life and maximum performance.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] Lubricators give the moving parts a needed friction barrier, reduce metal corrosion and keep vanes sealed properly against the cylinder walls.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] Even the so-called lube-free air starters require lubrication to prolong trouble free life.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] Two basic lubricator devices are typically employed.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] One is an in-line or reservoir type that typically stores up to 2 quarts of lubricant, and is installed along the air supply line.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] The second style of lubricator is a small one shot device that dispenses a measured amount of lubricant every time the starter is engaged.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] Installed directly onto the air inlet of the starter, the in-line lubricators are self priming pneumatic pumps that require a 1/4″ lubrication line piped from as far away as 4 feet.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] Air Starter lubricators perform best using misting type, non-detergent oils such as diesel fuel or Marvel Mystery oil.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] If emissions are a concern, there are environmentally friendly type lubricants available on the market.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] Not all air starters require lubrication.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] Turbine type air starters do not require air motor lubrication, although some turbine air starters do use an oil filled transmission that may require periodic inspections and maintenance.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] Compressed air has been used to start gas turbine engines using air impingement starting (in which air is directed at the engine turbine blades through nozzles in the turbine casing, used on US Navy General Electric J79 engines).
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] It is much more efficient to use an air turbine starter (ATS) which is usually mounted on an accessory gearbox.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] An early axial compressor turbojet had an ATS located in the compressor nose cone (eg particular variants of the J79).
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] Air impingement starting was not used for US military aircraft after the F-4B, A-5A and F-5 as the pneumatic energy requirement was several times greater than when using an air turbine starter.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] The gas turbine compressor required to start a J79 with impingement starting was sufficient to start two J79 engines simultaneously in a B-58 when using air turbine starters.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] An ATS has its own turbine and gears to change its low torque and high speed to low speed and high torque at the engine mounting pad.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] Further gears in the engine gearbox connect to the engine shaft (high pressure spool on multi-spool engines).
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] Compared with electric starters, air-starters have a higher power-to-weight ratio so are used on large engines as an electric starter would be too big and, with its cables, too heavy and expensive.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] However, for smaller engines, which don't need as much starter power, an electric starter is more suitable.
[src:axial-compressor/air-start-system] It has a dual function as a generator (is known as a starter/generator) at speeds above which the engine no longer requires starter assistance.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] The **air turborocket** is a form of combined-cycle jet engine.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] The basic layout includes a gas generator, which produces high pressure gas, that drives a turbine/compressor assembly which compresses atmospheric air into a combustion chamber.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] This mixture is then combusted before leaving the device through a nozzle and creating thrust.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] There are many different types of air turborockets.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] The various types generally differ in how the gas generator section of the engine functions.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] Air turborockets are often referred to as **turboramjets**, **turboramjet rockets**, **turborocket expanders**, and many others.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] As there is no consensus on which names apply to which specific concepts, various sources may use the same name for two different concepts.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] The benefit of this setup is increased specific impulse over that of a rocket.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] For the same carried mass of propellant as a rocket motor, the overall output of the air turborocket is much higher.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] In addition, it provides thrust throughout a much wider speed range than a ramjet, yet is much cheaper and easier to control than a gas turbine engine.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] The air turborocket fills a niche (in terms of cost, reliability, ruggedness, and duration of thrust) between the solid-fuel rocket motor and gas turbine engine for missile applications.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] A **turborocket** is a type of aircraft engine combining elements of a jet engine and a rocket.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] It typically comprises a multi-stage fan driven by a turbine, which is driven by the hot gases exhausting from a series of small rocket-like motors mounted around the turbine inlet.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust gases mix with the fan discharge air, and combust with the air from the compressor before exhausting through a convergent-divergent propelling nozzle.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] Once a jet engine goes high enough in an atmosphere, there is insufficient oxygen to burn the jet fuel.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] The idea behind a turborocket is to supplement the atmospheric oxygen with an onboard supply.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] This allows operation at a much higher altitude than a normal engine would allow.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] The turborocket design offers a mixture of benefits with drawbacks.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] It is not a true rocket, so it cannot operate in space.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] Cooling the engine is not a problem because the burner and its hot exhaust gases are located behind the turbine blades.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] The air turboramjet engine is a combined cycle engine that merges aspects of turbojet and ramjet engines.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] The turboramjet is a hybrid engine that essentially consists of a turbojet mounted inside a ramjet.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] The turbojet core is mounted inside a duct that contains a combustion chamber downstream of the turbojet nozzle.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] The turboramjet can be run in turbojet mode at takeoff and during low-speed flight but then switch to ramjet mode to accelerate to high Mach numbers.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] The operation of the engine is controlled using bypass flaps located just downstream of the diffuser.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] During low-speed flight, controllable flaps close the bypass duct and force air directly into the compressor section of the turbojet.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] During high-speed flight, the flaps block the flow into the turbojet, and the engine operates like a ramjet using the *aft* combustion chamber to produce thrust.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] The engine would start out operating as a turbojet during takeoff and while climbing to altitude.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] Upon reaching high subsonic speed, the portion of the engine downstream of the turbojet would be used as an afterburner to accelerate the plane above the speed of sound.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] At lower speeds, air passes through an inlet and is then compressed by an axial compressor.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] That compressor is driven by a turbine, which is powered by hot, high-pressure gas from a combustion chamber.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] These initial aspects are very similar to how a turbojet operates, however, there are several differences.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] The first is that the combustor in the turboramjet is often separate from the main airflow.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] Instead of combining air from the compressor with fuel to combust, the turboramjet combustor may use hydrogen and oxygen, carried on the aircraft, as its fuel for the combustor.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] The air compressed by the compressor bypasses the combustor and turbine section of the engine, where it is mixed with the turbine exhaust.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust can be designed to be fuel-rich (i.e., the combustor does not burn all the fuel) which, when mixed with the compressed air, creates a hot fuel-air mixture which is ready to burn again.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] More fuel is injected into this air where it is again combusted.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] The exhaust is ejected through a propelling nozzle, generating thrust.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] Picture shown lacks required bypass ducting around the compressor for ramjet operation.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] Shown is a low bypass turbojet with re-heat.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] The turboramjet engine is used when space is constrained, as it takes up less space than separate ramjet and turbojet engines.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] Since a ramjet must already be traveling at high speeds before it will start working, a ramjet-powered aircraft is incapable of taking off from a runway under its own power; that is the advantage of the turbojet, which is a member of the gas turbine family of engines.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] A turbojet does not rely purely on the motion of the engine to compress the incoming air flow; instead, the turbojet contains some additional rotating machinery that compresses incoming air and allows the engine to function during takeoff and at slow speeds.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] In applications which stay relatively in the atmosphere and require longer durations of lower thrust over a specific speed range the air turborocket can have a weight advantage over the standard solid fuel rocket motor.
[src:axial-compressor/air-turborocket] In terms of volumetric requirements, the rocket motor has the advantage due to the lack of inlet ducts and other air management devices.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] An **aircraft engine**, often referred to as an **aero engine**, is the power component of an aircraft propulsion system.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] Aircraft using power components are referred to as **powered flight**.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] Most aircraft engines are either piston engines or gas turbines, although a few have been rocket powered and in recent years many small UAVs have used electric motors.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] The market for aircraft engines, especially jet engines, has very high barriers to entry.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] Aircraft engines use highly advanced technology and materials, take around eight years and billions of dollars or euros to develop, and must pass exacting safety certifications by aviation safety authorities.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] Consequently, entering the engine market is extremely capital- and time-intensive, which helps protect existing manufacturers from competition.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] The last successful entry in the global market for jet engines was General Electric in the 1970s.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] These barriers to entry make the market very lucrative for existing manufacturers.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] As of 2025, the leading jet engine manufacturers reported shareholder returns from between 100 and 1,000 percent over the last five years, compared to small or negative returns for their principal clients, Airbus and Boeing.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] The engines themselves are typically sold at a loss, but manufacturers derive their profits from the sale of maintenance services and spare parts over the roughly thirty-year lifespan of an engine, following the razor and blades business model.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] This creates a perverse incentive for manufacturers to slow the production or delay the delivery of new engines, because they profit most from the use of old engines, which need more service and spare parts than new ones.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] This contributed to the unavailability of new engines, creating a bottleneck for Airbus and Boeing's efforts to increase aircraft production in the post-COVID resurgence of aviation after 2023.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] A radial engine has the cylinders placed in a circle around the crankshaft.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] The engine is air-cooled, which can be a problem since they may overheat.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] Compared to liquid-cooled engines, radial engines have the advantage of being more rugged and capable of absorbing damage.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] Rotating radial engines have the cylinders in a circle around the crankcase, as in a radial engine, (see above), but the crankshaft is fixed to the airframe and the propeller is fixed to the engine case, so that the crankcase and cylinders rotate.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] The advantage of this arrangement is that a satisfactory flow of cooling air is maintained even at low airspeeds, retaining the weight advantage and simplicity of a conventional air-cooled engine without one of their major drawbacks.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] The first practical rotary engine was the Gnome Omega designed by the Seguin brothers and first flown in 1909.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] Its relative reliability and good power to weight ratio changed aviation dramatically.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine is about one half the weight and size of a traditional four-stroke cycle piston engine of equal power output, and much lower in complexity.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] In an aircraft application, the power-to-weight ratio is very important, making the Wankel engine a good choice.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] Because the engine is typically constructed with an aluminium housing and a steel rotor, and aluminium expands more than steel when heated, a Wankel engine does not seize when overheated, unlike a piston engine.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] This is an important safety factor for aeronautical use.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] Considerable development of these designs started after World War II, but at the time the aircraft industry favored the use of turbine engines.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] It was believed that turbojet or turboprop engines could power all aircraft, from the largest to smallest designs.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine did not find many applications in aircraft, but was used by Mazda in a popular line of sports cars.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] The French company Citroën had developed Wankel powered RE-2 helicopter in 1970's.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] In modern times the Wankel engine has been used in motor gliders where the compactness, light weight, and smoothness are crucially important.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] Starting in the 1930s, attempts were made to produce a practical aircraft diesel engine.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] In general, Diesel engines are more reliable and much better suited to running for long periods of time at medium power settings.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] Improvements in Diesel technology in automobiles (leading to much better power-weight ratios), the Diesel's much better fuel efficiency, and the high relative taxation of AVGAS compared to Jet A1 in Europe have all seen a revival of interest in the use of diesels for aircraft.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] Thielert Aircraft Engines converted Mercedes Diesel automotive engines, certified them for aircraft use, and became an OEM provider to Diamond Aviation for their light twin.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] Financial problems have plagued Thielert, so Diamond's affiliate — Austro Engine — developed the new AE300 turbodiesel, also based on a Mercedes engine.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] A turboprop consists of an intake, reduction gearbox, compressor, combustor, turbine, and a propelling nozzle.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] Air enters the intake and is compressed by the compressor.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] Jet fuel is then added to the compressed air in the combustor, where it then combusts.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] The hot combustion gases expand through the turbine stages, generating power at the point of exhaust.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] Some of the power generated by the turbine is used to drive the compressor and electric generator.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] The gases are then exhausted from the turbine, but do not provide enough power to create a major portion of the total thrust, since almost all of the engine's power is used to drive the propeller.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] A **turboshaft** engine is a form of gas turbine that is optimized to produce shaft horsepower rather than jet thrust.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] The engine has two major parts assemblies: the 'gas generator' and the 'power section'.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] The gas generator consists of the compressor, combustion chambers with ignitors and fuel nozzles, and one or more stages of turbine.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] The power section consists of additional stages of turbines, a gear reduction system, and the shaft output.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] The gas generator creates the hot expanding gases to drive the power section; the engine accessories may be driven either by the gas generator or by the power section.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] A number of electrically powered aircraft, such as the QinetiQ Zephyr, have been designed since the 1960s.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] In France in late 2007, a conventional light aircraft powered by an 18 kW electric motor using lithium polymer batteries was flown, covering more than 50 kilometers (31 mi), the first electric airplane to receive a certificate of airworthiness.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] On 18 May 2020, the Pipistrel E-811 was the first electric aircraft engine to be awarded a type certificate by EASA for use in general aviation.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] The E-811 powers the Pipistrel Velis Electro.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] Many big companies, such as Siemens, are developing high-performance electric engines for aircraft use; also, SAE shows new developments in elements as pure Copper core electric motors with a better efficiency.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] A hybrid system as emergency back-up and for added power in take-off is offered for sale by Axter Aerospace, Madrid, Spain.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] The term *advanced technology engine* refers to the modern generation of jet engines.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] A rocket turbine engine is a combination of two types of propulsion engines: a liquid-propellant rocket and a turbine jet engine.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] Its power-to-weight ratio is a little higher than a regular jet engine, and it works at higher altitudes.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] At the April 2018 ILA Berlin Air Show, Munich-based research institute de:Bauhaus Luftfahrt presented a high-efficiency composite cycle engine for 2050, combining a geared turbofan with a piston engine core.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] The 11,200 lb (49.7 kN) engine could power a 50-seat regional jet.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] Its cruise TSFC would be 11.5 g/kN/s (0.406 lb/lbf/hr) for an overall engine efficiency of 48.2%, for a burner temperature of 1,700 K (1,430 °C), an overall pressure ratio of 38 and a peak pressure of 30 MPa (300 bar).
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] Although engine weight increases by 30%, aircraft fuel consumption is reduced by 15%.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] Sponsored by the European Commission under Framework 7 project LEMCOTEC, Bauhaus Luftfahrt, MTU Aero Engines and GKN Aerospace presented the concept in 2015, raising the overall engine pressure ratio to over 100 for a 15.2% fuel burn reduction compared to 2025 engines.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] On multi-engine aircraft, engine positions are numbered from left to right from the point of view of the pilot looking forward, so for example on a four-engine aircraft such as the Boeing 747, engine No.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] 1 is on the left side, farthest from the fuselage, while engine No.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] 3 is on the right side nearest to the fuselage.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] In the case of the twin-engine English Electric Lightning, which has two fuselage-mounted jet engines one above the other, engine No.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] 1 is below and to the front of engine No.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] Refineries blend Avgas with tetraethyllead (TEL) to achieve these high octane ratings, a practice that governments no longer permit for gasoline intended for road vehicles.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] The shrinking supply of TEL and the possibility of environmental legislation banning its use have made a search for replacement fuels for general aviation aircraft a priority for pilots’ organizations.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] Model aircraft typically use nitro engines (also known as "glow engines" due to the use of a glow plug) powered by glow fuel, a mixture of methanol, nitromethane, and lubricant.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] Electrically powered model airplanes and helicopters are also commercially available.
[src:axial-compressor/aircraft-engine] Small multicopter UAVs are almost always powered by electricity, but larger gasoline-powered designs are under development.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] An **axial compressor** is a type of gas compressor that continuously pressurizes a working fluid.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] It is a rotating, airfoil-based device in which the fluid flows primarily in one direction parallel to the axis of rotation.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] This distinguishes axial compressors from other types of rotating compressors, such as centrifugal compressors, axi-centrifugal compressors, and mixed-flow compressors, in which the fluid flowing includes a significant radial component directed outward from the axis of rotation.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] The rotor blades exert torque on the fluid, increasing its energy as it passes through the compressor.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] The stationary blades, or stators, slow the fluid, converting the circumferential component of flowing into pressure.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Compressors are typically driven by an electric motor, a steam turbine, or a gas turbine.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Axial flow compressors produce a continuous flow of compressed gas.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] They exhibit high efficiency and large mass flow rate in relation to the size of their cross-section.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] They are more intricate and expensive relative to other designs, requiring several rows of airfoils to achieve a large pressure rise.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Axial compressors are integral to the design of large gas turbines such as jet engines, high speed ship engines, and small scale power stations.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] They are also used in industrial applications such as large volume air separation plants, blast furnace air, fluid catalytic cracking air, and propane dehydrogenation.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Additionally, due to their performance and operability across the flight envelope (safe operational limits for an aircraft), they are widely used in aerospace applications.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Axial compressors consist of alternating rows of rotating and stationary airfoils.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] The rotating airfoils, or rotors, are mounted on a rotating drum, which is driven by a central shaft.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] The stationary airfoils, known as vanes or stators, are mounted to a tubular casing.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] One row of rotors and one row of stators together form a stage.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] The rotors impart kinetic energy to the working fluid, increasing its velocity in the axial and circumferential directions.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] The stators convert the increased kinetic energy into static pressure through diffusion and redirect the flow direction of the fluid to prepare it for the rotor blades of the next stage.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] The area between the rotor drum and casing decreases along the flow direction to maintain an optimum Mach number as the fluid is compressed.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Rotor passages can be designed to achieve diffusive pressure rise, leading to a higher pressure rise per stage.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] The ratio of pressure rise in the rotor to the total pressure rise of the stage is known as the degree of reaction.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] The increase in pressure produced by a single stage is limited by the relative velocity between the rotor and the fluid, and the turning and diffusion capabilities of the airfoils.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] A typical stage in a commercial compressor will produce a pressure increase of between 15% and 60% (pressure ratios of 1.15–1.6) at design conditions with a polytropic efficiency in the region of 90–95%.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] To achieve different pressure ratios, axial compressors are designed with different numbers of stages and rotational speeds.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] As a rule of thumb, it can be assumed that each stage in a given compressor has the same temperature rise (ΔT).
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Therefore, at the entry, temperature (Tstage) to each stage must increase progressively through the compressor and the ratio (Delta T)/(Tstage) entry must decrease, thus implying a progressive reduction in stage pressure ratio through the unit.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Hence the rear stage develops a significantly lower pressure ratio than the first stage.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Higher stage pressure ratios are also possible if the relative velocity between fluid and rotors is supersonic, but this is achieved at the expense of efficiency and operability.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Such compressors, with stage pressure ratios of over 2, are only used where minimizing the compressor size, weight or complexity is critical, such as in military jets.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] The airfoil profiles are optimized and matched for specific velocities and turning.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Although compressors can be run at other conditions with different flows, speeds, or pressure ratios, this can result in an efficiency penalty or even a partial or complete breakdown in flow (known as compressor stall and pressure surge respectively).
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Thus, a practical limit on the number of stages, and the overall pressure ratio, comes from the interaction of the different stages when required to work away from the design conditions.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] These "off-design" conditions can be mitigated to a certain extent by providing some flexibility in the compressor.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] This is achieved normally through the use of adjustable stators or with valves that can bleed fluid from the main flow between stages (inter-stage bleed).
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Modern jet engines use a series of compressors, running at different speeds; to supply air at around 40:1 pressure ratio for combustion with sufficient flexibility for all flight conditions.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] The law of moment of momentum states that the sum of the moments of external forces acting on a fluid which is temporarily occupying the control volume is equal to the net change of angular momentum flux through the control volume.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] The swirling fluid enters the control volume at radius, $r_{1}\,$ , with tangential velocity, $V_{w1}\,$ , and leaves at radius, $r_{2}\,$ , with tangential velocity, $V_{w2}\,$ .
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] are the absolute velocities at the inlet and outlet respectively.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] are the axial flow velocities at the inlet and outlet respectively.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] are the swirl velocities at the inlet and outlet respectively.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] are the blade-relative velocities at the inlet and outlet respectively.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Axial compressor performance is shown on a compressor map, also known as a characteristic, by plotting pressure ratio and efficiency against corrected mass flow at different values of corrected compressor speed.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Axial compressors, particularly near their design point are usually amenable to analytical treatment, and a good estimate of their performance can be made before they are first run on a rig.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] The compressor map shows the complete running range, i.e. off-design, of the compressor from ground idle to its highest corrected rotor speed, which for a civil engine may occur at top-of-climb, or, for a military combat engine, at take-off on a cold day.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Not shown is the sub-idle performance region needed for analysing normal ground and in-flight windmill start behaviour.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Stage pressure ratio against flow rate is lower than for a no-loss stage as shown.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Losses are due to blade friction, flow separation, unsteady flow and vane-blade spacing.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] The performance of a compressor is defined according to its design.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] But in actual practice, the operating point of the compressor deviates from the design point; this is known as *off-design operation*.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] The value of $(\tan \beta _{2}+\tan \alpha _{1})\,$ doesn't change for a wide range of operating points till stalling.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Also $\alpha _{1}=\alpha _{3}\,$ because of minor change in air angle at rotor and stator, where $\alpha _{3}\,$ is diffuser blade angle.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] for positive values of J, slope of the curve is negative and vice versa.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] There are multiple modes of instability an axial compressor could undergo.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Edward Greitzer used a Helmholtz resonator type of compression system model to predict the transient response of a compression system after a small perturbation superimposed on a steady operating condition.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] He found a non-dimensional parameter which predicted which mode of compressor instability, rotating stall or surge, would result.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] The parameter used the rotor speed, the Helmholtz resonator frequency of the system, and an "effective length" of the compressor duct.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] These produced a critical value which predicted either rotating stall or surge where the slope of pressure ratio against flow changed from negative to positive.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] In the plot of pressure-flow rate, the line separating graph between two regions – unstable and stable – is known as the **surge line**.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] This line is formed by joining surge points at different rotational speeds.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Surging is the unstable flow in axial compressors due to complete breakdown of the steady through flow.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] This phenomenon affects the performance of compressor and is undesirable.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] The following explanation for surging refers to running a compressor at a constant speed on a rig and gradually reducing the exit area by closing a valve.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] What happens, i.e. crossing the surge line, is caused by the compressor trying to deliver air, still running at the same speed, to a higher exit pressure.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Suppose the initial operating point *D* ( ${\dot {m}},P_{D}\,$ ) at some rotational speed *N*.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] On decreasing the flow-rate at same rotational speed along the characteristic curve by partial closing of the valve, the pressure in the pipe increases which will be taken care by increase in input pressure at the compressor.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] With further increase in pressure up to point *P* (surge point), compressor pressure will increase.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Further moving towards left keeping rotational speed constant, pressure in pipe will increase but compressor pressure will decrease leading to back air flow towards the compressor.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Due to this back flow, pressure in pipe will decrease because this unequal pressure condition cannot stay for a long period of time.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Though valve position is set for lower flow rate say point *G* but compressor will work according to normal stable operation point say *E*, so path *E*–*F*–*P*–*G*–*E* will be followed leading to breakdown of flow, hence pressure in the compressor falls further to point *H*( $P_{H}\,$ ).
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] This increase and decrease of pressure in pipe will occur repeatedly in pipe and compressor following the cycle *E*–*F*–*P*–*G*–*H*–*E* also known as the surge cycle.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] This phenomenon will cause vibrations in the whole machine and may lead to mechanical failure.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] That is why left portion of the curve from the surge point is called unstable region and may cause damage to the machine.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] So the recommended operation range is on the right side of the surge line.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Stall is a phenomenon affecting the performance of the compressor whereby flow separation occurs at the compressor blades, leading to reduced compression and a drop in engine power.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] An analysis is made of rotating stall in compressors of many stages, finding conditions under which a flow distortion can occur which is steady in a traveling reference frame, even though upstream total and downstream static pressure are constant.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] In the compressor, a pressure-rise hysteresis is assumed.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Two types of stall are distinguished: *positive stall,* where flow separation occurs on the suction side of the blade, and *negative stall,* where it occurs on the pressure side.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] In practice, negative stall is negligible compared to positive stall as flow separation is least likely to occur on the pressure side of the blade.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] In a multi-stage compressor, at the high pressure stages, axial velocity is very small.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Stalling value decreases with a small deviation from the design point causing stall near the hub and tip regions whose size increases with decreasing flow rates.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] They grow larger at very low flow rate and affect the entire blade height.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Non-uniformity of air flow in the rotor blades may disturb local air flow in the compressor without upsetting it.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] The compressor continues to work normally but with reduced compression.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Thus, rotating stall decreases the effectiveness of the compressor.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] In a rotor with blades moving say towards right.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Let some blades receives flow at higher incidence, this blade will stop positively.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] It creates obstruction in the passage between the blade to its left and itself.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Thus the left blade will receive the flow at higher incidence and the blade to its right with decreased incidence.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] The left blade will experience more stall while the blade to its right will experience lesser stall.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Towards the right stalling will decrease whereas it will increase towards its left.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Movement of the rotating stall can be observed depending upon the chosen reference frame.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] From an energy exchange point of view axial compressors are reversed turbines.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Steam-turbine designer Charles Algernon Parsons, for example, recognized that a turbine which produced work by virtue of a fluid's static pressure (i.e. a reaction turbine) could have its action reversed to act as an air compressor, calling it a turbo compressor or pump.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] His rotor and stator blading described in one of his patents had little or no camber although in some cases the blade design was based on propeller theory.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] The machines, driven by steam turbines, were used for industrial purposes such as supplying air to blast furnaces.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Parsons supplied the first commercial axial flow compressor for use in a lead smelter in 1901.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Parsons' machines had low efficiencies, later attributed to blade stall, and were soon replaced with more efficient centrifugal compressors.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Brown Boveri & Cie produced "reversed turbine" compressors, driven by gas turbines, with blading derived from aerodynamic research which were more efficient than centrifugal types when pumping large flow rates of 40,000 ft3/min (19 m3/s) at pressures up to 45 psi (310 kPa).
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Because early axial compressors were not efficient enough a number of papers in the early 1920s claimed that a practical axial-flow turbojet engine would be impossible to construct.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Griffith published a seminal paper in 1926, noting that the reason for the poor performance was that existing compressors used flat blades and were essentially "flying stalled".
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] He showed that the use of airfoils instead of the flat blades would increase efficiency to the point where a practical jet engine was a real possibility.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] He concluded the paper with a basic diagram of such an engine, which included a second turbine that was used to power a propeller.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Although Griffith was well known due to his earlier work on metal fatigue and stress measurement, little work appears to have started as a direct result of his paper.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] The only obvious effort was a test-bed compressor built by Hayne Constant, Griffith's colleague at the Royal Aircraft Establishment.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Other early jet efforts, notably those of Frank Whittle and Hans von Ohain, were based on the more robust and better understood centrifugal compressor which was widely used in superchargers.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Griffith had seen Whittle's work in 1929 and dismissed it, noting a mathematical error, and going on to claim that the frontal size of the engine would make it useless on a high-speed aircraft.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Real work on axial-flow engines started in the late 1930s, in several efforts that all started at about the same time.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] In England, Hayne Constant reached an agreement with the steam turbine company Metropolitan-Vickers (Metrovick) in 1937, starting their turboprop effort based on the Griffith design in 1938.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] In 1940, after the successful run of Whittle's centrifugal-flow design, their effort was re-designed as a pure jet, the Metrovick F.2.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] In the United States, both Lockheed and General Electric were awarded contracts in 1941 to develop axial-flow engines, the former a pure jet, the latter a turboprop.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Northrop also started their own project to develop a turboprop, which the US Navy eventually contracted in 1943.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Westinghouse also entered the race in 1942, their project proving to be the only successful one of the US efforts, later becoming the J30.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] As Griffith had originally noted in 1929, the large frontal size of the centrifugal compressor caused it to have higher drag than the narrower axial-flow type.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Additionally the axial-flow design could improve its compression ratio simply by adding additional stages and making the engine slightly longer.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] In the centrifugal-flow design the compressor itself had to be larger in diameter, which was much more difficult to fit properly into a thin and aerodynamic aircraft fuselage (although not dissimilar to the profile of radial engines already in widespread use).
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] On the other hand, centrifugal-flow designs remained much less complex (the major reason they "won" in the race to flying examples) and therefore have a role in places where size and streamlining are not so important.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] In the jet engine application, the compressor faces a wide variety of operating conditions.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] On the ground at high power settings the inlet pressure is high, inlet speed zero, and the compressor spun at a variety of speeds as the power is applied.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Once in flight the inlet pressure drops, but the inlet speed increases (due to the forward motion of the aircraft) to recover some of this pressure, and the compressor tends to run at a single speed for long periods of time.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] There is simply no "perfect" compressor for this wide range of operating conditions.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Fixed geometry compressors, like those used on early jet engines, are limited to a design pressure ratio of about 4:1 or 5:1.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] As with any heat engine, fuel efficiency is strongly related to the compression ratio, so there is very strong financial need to improve the compressor stages beyond these sorts of ratios.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Additionally the compressor may stall if the inlet conditions change abruptly, a common problem on early engines.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] In some cases, if the stall occurs near the front of the engine, all of the stages from that point on will stop compressing the air.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] In this situation the energy required to run the compressor drops suddenly, and the remaining hot air in the rear of the engine allows the turbine to speed up the whole engine dramatically.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] This condition, known as surging, was a major problem on early engines and often led to the turbine or compressor breaking and shedding blades.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] For all of these reasons, axial compressors on modern jet engines are considerably more complex than those on earlier designs.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] All compressors have an optimum point relating rotational speed and pressure, with higher compressions requiring higher speeds.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Early engines were designed for simplicity, and used a single large compressor spinning at a single speed.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Later designs added a second turbine and divided the compressor into low-pressure and high-pressure sections, the latter spinning faster.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] This *two-spool* design, pioneered on the Bristol Olympus, resulted in increased efficiency.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Further increases in efficiency may be realised by adding a third spool, but in practice the added complexity increases maintenance costs to the point of negating any economic benefit.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] That said, there are several three-spool engines in use, perhaps the most famous being the Rolls-Royce RB211 (and its successor, the Rolls-Royce Trent), used on a wide variety of commercial aircraft.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] As an aircraft changes speed or altitude, the pressure of the air at the inlet to the compressor will vary.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] In order to "tune" the compressor for these changing conditions, designs starting in the 1950s would "bleed" air out of the middle of the compressor in order to avoid trying to compress too much air in the final stages.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] This was also used to help start the engine, allowing it to be spun up without compressing much air by bleeding off as much as possible.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Bleed systems were already commonly used anyway, to provide airflow into the turbine stage where it was used to cool the turbine blades, as well as provide pressurized air for the air conditioning systems inside the aircraft.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] A more advanced design, the *variable stator*, used blades that can be individually rotated around their axis, as opposed to the power axis of the engine.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] For start up they are rotated to "closed", reducing compression, and then are rotated back into the airflow as the external conditions require.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] The General Electric J79 was the first major example of a variable stator design, and today it is a common feature of most military engines.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Closing the variable stators progressively, as compressor speed falls, reduces the slope of the surge (or stall) line on the operating characteristic (or map), improving the surge margin of the installed unit.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] By incorporating variable stators in the first five stages, General Electric Aircraft Engines has developed a ten-stage axial compressor capable of operating at a 23:1 design pressure ratio.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] The relative motion of the blades to the fluid adds velocity or pressure or both to the fluid as it passes through the rotor.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] The fluid velocity is increased through the rotor, and the stator converts kinetic energy to pressure energy.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Some diffusion also occurs in the rotor in most practical designs.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] The increase in velocity of the fluid is primarily in the tangential direction (swirl) and the stator removes this angular momentum.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] The pressure rise results in a stagnation temperature rise.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] For a given geometry the temperature rise depends on the square of the tangential Mach number of the rotor row.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Current turbofan engines have fans that operate at Mach 1.7 or more, and require significant containment and noise suppression structures to reduce blade loss damage and noise.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] A map shows the performance of a compressor and allows determination of optimal operating conditions.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] It shows the mass flow along the horizontal axis, typically as a percentage of the design mass flow rate, or in actual units.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] The pressure rise is indicated on the vertical axis as a ratio between inlet and exit stagnation pressures.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] A surge or stall line identifies the boundary to the left of which the compressor performance rapidly degrades and identifies the maximum pressure ratio that can be achieved for a given mass flow.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Contours of efficiency are drawn as well as performance lines for operation at particular rotational speeds.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Operating efficiency is highest close to the stall line.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] If the downstream pressure is increased beyond the maximum possible the compressor will stall and become unstable.
[src:axial-compressor/axial-compressor] Typically the instability will be at the Helmholtz frequency of the system, taking the downstream plenum into account.
